    <h2 class="articleTitle">Desktop Motherboard Buying Guide</h2>

    <p class="generalText"><strong>By Juan Aguilar</strong></p>
    <p class="generalText"><em>Updated: September 15, 2019</em></p>
    <hr />

    <br />

    <h4 class="articleTitle">Motherboard Chipset</h4>
    <p class="generalText">
        The motherboard chipset dictates compatibility with other PC components. It determines the support for PC parts such as the CPU, RAM, and etc. The following sections explain what to look for in a chipset and motherboard. One example is chipsets for AMD Ryzen. Below is a picture of different chipsets and which series of Ryzen that they're compatible with. 
    </p>
    <img class="articleImage" src="/images/Blog/Hardware/DesktopMotherboardBuyingGuide/Zen2MoboSupport.jpg" />
    <p class="generalText">
        As of right now, X570 is the best chipset with the most features. As you go down the list, chipsets become cheaper and have less features. 
    </p>

    <h4 class="articleTitle">Processor Socket</h4>
    <p class="generalText">
        The socket on the motherboard is used to house a processor. Processors are designed to fit in a certain socket. The latest AMD processors use an AM4 socket. The latest Intel processors use an LGA 1151v2 socket. AMD processors use pins to slot into a socket. One bent pin can ruin the CPU so be careful when inserting. Intel processors have pads instead of pins. You can easily slot them into place and don't have to worry about bent pins. Usually, people choose a CPU they want then find a motherboard with the right socket.
    </p>
